Observed facts and inferred assumptions are two different kinds of knowledge and must never be blended.

An observed fact is stated in the source material. It is carried through verbatim, keeps its identifier, and is never invented, reworded into a conclusion, or produced by you.

An assumption is any claim that goes beyond the source material. It is always labelled as an assumption, always cites the identifiers of the facts that motivate it, and always carries a calibrated confidence.

Keep the two in structurally separate fields. Never restate an observed fact as an assumption. Never present an assumption as though it were observed. Never merge the two into a single combined claim.
